# Implementation Rules

## Scope Discipline
Implement only the requested module.

Do not:
- expand scope
- build future modules early
- modify unrelated modules
- introduce phase 2 or phase 3 features

Stay inside the requested scope.

---

## Change Discipline
Do not rewrite stable code without explicit instruction.

Do not refactor unrelated modules while implementing a requested feature.

Touch only what is necessary for the requested scope.

---

## Implementation Pattern
Follow this structure for each feature:

- components/
- hooks/
- services/
- schemas/
- types/

Keep feature logic inside feature boundaries.

---

## Code Discipline
- Keep components small
- Keep services explicit
- Keep hooks focused
- Prefer clarity over abstraction
- Do not over-engineer MVP

Avoid unnecessary abstraction.

---

## Safety Rules
Do not:
- weaken RLS
- bypass permissions
- remove audit
- move business logic into UI
- duplicate business logic across layers

Protect system integrity.

---

## UX Rules
- mobile-first
- fast
- touch-friendly
- low-friction
- simple

Do not overbuild UI.

---

## Testing Rules
Every module must include:

- unit coverage for business logic
- UI coverage for critical interactions
- permission coverage for guarded actions

Do not skip meaningful tests.

---

## Output Discipline
When implementing:
- summarize what changed
- list created files
- list modified files
- note assumptions
- note risks

Keep implementation explicit.